<TITLE> Hartal not enforced to wrest power: Selim </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 14 (bdnews24.com)--The hartal has been called in the national interest to protect public property, an orgnaiser of a citizen's pressure group said. "We are not enforcing the strike to wrest power from the government. We have assured the nation that we will not abuse the strike," Mujahidul Islam Selim, one of the main organisers of the pressure committee, told bdnews24.com in the Paltan intersection. "We have called the strike in national interest," said Selim, the general secretary of Communist Party of Bangladesh. The National Committee on Protection of Oil, Gas, Mineral Resources, Power and Ports on Monday called a half-day shutdown from 6am in capital Dhaka to protest the government's recently announced gas exploration deals with international companies. "Those who are now opposing hartal have already enforced some hundreds of hartals in the last five years. BNP and Awami League have already used up the hartal quota," he said. "Hartal is our democratic right. The government backed by the military discourages strike. The democratic government is also against enforcement of strike to safeguard democracy. "But, we have to enforce strike to realise people's demands," Selim said. bd
